This is a documentation of DBERlibR, which represents Discipline-based Education Research library R. The package runs R scripts to clean the data, merge/bind multiple data sets (as necessary), check assumption(s) for a specific statistical technique (as necessary), run the main test data analysis, and export the analysis output(s) all at once. The output(s) contain(s) a sample interpretation of the results for the convenience of users. Users need to prepare the data file as instructed, save it in the folder designated as a working directory in RStudio, load all dependencies, and type a function in the R console to conduct a specific data analysis. 

## Package Installation

The “DBERlibR” package is currently published on GitHub, so you need to follow the steps to install a package from GitHub, as instructed below. Please make sure to have R (version 4.0 or newer) (https://cloud.r-project.org/) and the most recent RStudio (https://www.rstudio.com/products/rstudio/download/) installed on your machine before proceeding. 

1. First, you need to install the “devtools” package in your RStudio if you haven’t done so yet. Please refer to the instructions for installing devtools, available at https://www.r-project.org/nosvn/pandoc/devtools.html. You can do this from CRAN; just copy/type the line below in your R console and hit the Enter key.
```{r, results='hide', message=FALSE}
install.packages("devtools", repos="http://cran.us.r-project.org")
```
2. You need to have a working development environment before loading the package “devtools” in RStudio. Please follow Step 2 in the instruction on devtools linked above. For example, you need to  download and install RTools if the operating system of your machine is Windows; follow the instruction available https://cran.r-project.org/bin/windows/Rtools/rtools40.html (You may want to refer to a YouTube video on how to install RTools40: e.g., https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=njZBf34Akgo). 

3. Once you have a working development environment, load the “devtools” package in RStudio; just copy/type the line below in your R console and hit the Enter key.
```{r, results='hide', message=FALSE, warning=FALSE}
library(devtools)
```
4. Now you’re ready to install the package “DBERlibR” from GitHub. In most cases, you just use install_github(“author/package”). So, you can just copy/type the line below in your R console and hit the Enter key.
```{r, results='hide', message=FALSE}
install_github("HelikarLabPersonal/DBERlibR", repos="http://cran.us.r-project.org")
```
If you get the question, “Do you want to install from sources the package which needs compilation?”, this often means that the package has been updated recently on CRAN but the binary isn’t yet available for your OS (can take a day or two). There are probably other scenarios when the binary isn’t available for your platform. If you say no, you won’t get the most recent version. But this might be just fine unless you were specifically installing because of an update. If you say yes, the package will be built from source locally. If it has compiled code and you’ve never set up build tools for R, then this won’t actually succeed.

## Load DBERlibR and other Dependencies, Set Working Directory, and Save Data File(s) in that Directory

Load DBERlibR by typing/copying the line below in the R console and hitting the Enter key.

```{r load_DBERlibR}
library(DBERlibR)
```

Then, load all dependencies (other packages imported in DBERlibR) by typing/copying the line below in the R console and hitting the Enter key. This function will download all dependencies that don't exist in your RStudio and then automatically load them. You need to run this function [i.e., loadpackage()] whenever you open RStudio to use DBERlibR (you don't need to repeat this function unless you close and re-open RStudio).

```{r, results='hide', message=FALSE, warning=FALSE}
loadpackages()
```

You need to set “Working Directory” under the “Session” menu in R Studio. The directory should be a folder where (all) data file(s) is(are) saved because the functions in this package import accurately named data file(s) from the working directory. Please download the sample data folder (4 csv files in it) from “https://github.com/HelikarLabPersonal/DBERlibR” to test the package. You need to add a GitZip extension to your browser to download a folder from GitHub (refer to a YouTube video on how to do it: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=6dnzDILMobU). Once downloaded unzipped, save all 4 csv files in the working directory you’ve set. 

## Data Preparation

The data should include only (student) id and questions (no other data like demographic information; you should save other data in a separate file along with id if you have them). The question data should be binary (i.e., 1 for correct answers, 0 for incorrect answers); if your data contains multiple-choice answers, you must transform them into binary data. For your reference, the data file should look like the sample below. The data file should be in the "csv" format.

![Data Format](https://helikarlabpersonal.github.io/DBERlibR/data_format.png)

As you can see in the data table above, the questions were named Q1, Q2, Q3, and so on, but you can name the questions differently; please make sure to use the same question name across different data sets (i.e. treatment group pre-test data, treatment group post-test data, control group pre-test data, and control group post-test data). Blank cells indicate skipped answers; these blank cells will be treated as incorrect in the process of data preparation. Please do not fill the blank cells (i.e., skipped answers) with any simbol (e.g., "NA", "99"); those simbols will cause an error in data preparation/analysis. An csv data file exported from online survey platform like Qualtrics may contain two header rows (one for question number and another for question wordings); you need to leave only one header with id and question numbers. Please open the sample data files to see how they are prepared consistently. 

You need to save the data file exactly the same as the sample data files (use the same file names): "data_treat_pre.csv" for the treatment group's pre-test data; "data_treat_post.csv" for the treatment group's post-test data; "data_ctrl_pre.csv" for the control group's pre-test data; and "data_ctrl_post.csv" for the control group's post-test data.

Skipped answers in the data file(s) (i.e., blank cells in the dataframe above) will be treated as incorrect in this package. Too many skipped answers may skew the results of data analysis. By default, students with more than 15% of skipped answers will be excluded from data analysis to prevent skewed results. If you don't agree with this rate of 15%, you can provide a different rate by responding to the following prompt (You need to respond to this prompt whenever you run a function in this package):

```{r, message=FALSE, warning=FALSE, echo=FALSE}
print("Please enter an alternative rate in a decimal format (e.g., 0.1 for 10%, 0.25 for 25%): ")
```

If you're fine with the default rate of 15%, just hit the 'Enter' key (i.e., no input) when you see the prompt above. 

If you have students' demographic information and want to examine the differences of demographic subgroups (e.g., male vs. female), you should save other data in a separate file along with id (the same id as in the test data file(s)). Although The data format should look like the one below. Please DO NOT convert the subgroup label to a numeric code; it will be hard to read the results if you use a numeric code. 

![Demographic Data Format](https://helikarlabpersonal.github.io/DBERlibR/data_format_demo.png)

## Item Analysis Function: "itemanalysis()"

The item analysis function requires users to type a data file name as shown in the sample code below. You can input any of the data file names (i.e., "data_treat_pre.csv", "data_treat_post.csv", "data_ctrl_pre.csv", or "data_ctrl_post.csv") as they become available for item analysis. 

```{r, results='hide', message=FALSE}
# You can copy and paste the following function into the console panel of RStudio: itemanalysis("data_treat_pre.csv"), itemanalysis("data_ctrl_pre.csv"), itemanalysis("data_treat_post.csv"), or itemanalysis("data_ctrl_pre.csv")
```

```{r, message=FALSE, warning=FALSE, echo=FALSE}

  # Reading
  data_original <- read_csv("data_treat_pre.csv",col_types = cols())


  # Calculate average scores
  data_original[is.na(data_original)]= 0
  # colnames(data_original) <- paste( colnames(data_original), file_name, sep = "_")
  data_original <- data_original %>% mutate(avg_score = rowMeans(data_original[,-1]))

  # ggplots: difficulty index
  difficulty_data <- data_original[,c(-1)] %>% colMeans() %>% t() %>% as.data.frame() %>% t()
  difficulty_data <- reshape::melt(round(difficulty_data,2), id.vars=c("Q_id"))  %>% dplyr::select(-X2)
  colnames(difficulty_data) = c("q.number","difficulty_index")
  plot_difficulty<- ggplot(difficulty_data, aes(x= difficulty_index , y= reorder(q.number,difficulty_index))) +
    geom_point(alpha=0.9) +
    geom_vline(xintercept = 0.2, color ="red")+
    geom_hline(yintercept = difficulty_data$q.number[length(data_original)-1],color="blue") +
    ggtitle("Difficulty Plot",subtitle = "Ordered by proportions")+
    xlab("Proportion")+ ylab("Question Item Number\n\n\n\n\n") +theme_minimal() + geom_text_repel(aes(label = round(difficulty_index,2)))

  # Create data subset: difficulty index lower than 0.2
  toodifficultitems <- subset(difficulty_data, difficulty_index < 0.2)
  toodifficultitems_nrow <- nrow(toodifficultitems)

  # ggplots: discrimination index
  discrimination_data <- cor(data_original[,-1]) %>% as.data.frame()
  plot_discrimination <- ggplot(discrimination_data, aes(x=avg_score , y= reorder (colnames(discrimination_data),avg_score))) + geom_point() +
    geom_vline(xintercept = 0.2, color ="red")+
    xlab("Relationship Coefficient") +
    ylab("Question Item Number") + ggtitle("Discrimination Plot") +
    theme_minimal() + geom_text_repel(aes(label = round(avg_score,2)))

  # Create data subset: discrimination index lower than 0.2
  qnumber <- colnames(discrimination_data)
  discrimination_index <- round(discrimination_data$avg_score,2)
  discrimination_df <- data.frame(qnumber,discrimination_index)
  nondiscriminantitems <- subset(discrimination_df, discrimination_index < 0.2)
  nondiscriminantitems_nrow <- nrow(nondiscriminantitems)
```

The function will display a message and prompt to determine 'students with too many skipped answers' to be excluded from data analysis. Once you respond to this prompt (i.e., either provide an alternative rate or just hit the Enter key), the function automatically reads and cleans the data (e.g., deleting students with too many skipped answers, converting missing values to "0"), calculates difficulty and discriminant scores, displays all results in the Console and Plots panels of RStudio, and exports the results to an Excel file, which is saved in the working directory. The Excel file name follows the data file name used for item analysis; for example, if you've input "data_treat_pre.csv" in the function, then the output Excel file name contains "treat_pre." The function also generates plots in the jpeg file format to visualize the results; the jpeg file name follows the data file name as well so that you can easily find the results of the item analysis you've just run.

Item difficulty refers to the proportion of students that correctly answered the item, scaled 0 to 1. Ideal values are known to be slightly higher than midway between a chance to be chosen (i.e., 1 divided by the number of choices) and a perfect score (1) for the item. In common, values below 0.2 are considered to indicate "very difficult" items and need to be reviewed for possible confusing language, removed from the test, and/or identified as an area for re-instruction to improve test instruments. In addition to improving the test instrument, the results of item difficulty analysis inform the areas of weakness in students’ knowledge to be taken into consideration in improving teaching modules. The difficulty plot is shown below. 

```{r, message=FALSE, warning=FALSE, echo=FALSE}
  # Print difficulty data results
  print("Item Analysis Results - Difficulty")
  print(difficulty_data)
  print("The result above has been exported to an Excel file, of which file name includes 'itemanalysis_outputs,' in the working directory.")
  plot(plot_difficulty)
  print("Please refer to 'Difficulty Plot' in the 'Plots' panel. The plot has also been exported to an image file, of which file name includes 'itemanalysis_difficulty_plot,' in the working directory.")
  if (toodifficultitems_nrow > 0) {
    print("As you can see in the plot, the question items of which difficulty index turned out to be lower than 0.2 are as follows:")
    print(toodifficultitems$Q_id)
  } else {
    print("As you can see in the plot, none of the difficulty indixes was found to be lower than 0.2")
  }
```

The proportions in the generated difficulty plot above are ordered by their size, and the plot displays a vertical red-colored line that represents the threshold of 0.2 so that you can instantly find the question items that warrant your attention for improvement. The plot above does not have any item of which proportion size is below 0.2. 

Meanwhile, item discrimination represents the relationship between how well students did on the item and their total test performance, ranging from 0 to 1. The closer to 1, the better; the scales of 0.2 or higher are generally known to be acceptable. Items with discrimination values near or less than zero need to be removed from the test. For example, negative values indicate that students who did poorly on the test did better on that item than those who overall did well, which doesn't make sense. Removing the items highlighted in red, especially with negative values, in the table may need to be considered, or improving instructions related to the items with low values should be considered to increase the values. The discrimination plot is shown below (ignore the R codes below since it's just to show how the plot is generated; that is, the function automatically runs the codes).

```{r, message=FALSE, warning=FALSE, echo=FALSE}

    # Print discrimination data results
  print("Item Analysis Results - Discrimination:")
  print(discrimination_df)
  print("The result above has been exported to an Excel file, of which file name includes 'itemanalysis_outputs,' in the working directory.")
  plot(plot_discrimination)
  print("Please refer to 'Discrimination Plot' in the 'Plots' panel. The plot has also been exported to an image file, of which file name includes 'itemanalysis_discrimination_plot,' in the working directory.")
  if (nondiscriminantitems_nrow > 0) {
    print("As you can see in the plot, the question items of which discrimination index turned out to be lower than 0.2 are as follows:")
    print(nondiscriminantitems$qnumber)
  } else {
